{{expand French|Abbaye de Bellebranche|date=September 2014|topic=struct}}
'''Bellebranche Abbey''' ({{lang-fr|Abbaye de Bellebranche}}) is a former [[Cistercian]] [[monastery]] located in [[Saint-Brice, Mayenne|Saint-Brice]], [[Mayenne]], [[France]], founded in 1152 and suppressed during the [[French Revolution]].

==History==
Bellebranche Abbey was established by monks from [[Louroux Abbey]], in [[Anjou]], in 1150. The foundation was made final on 27 July 1152 by the gift of [[Robert III de Sablé]]. His son, [[Robert IV de Sablé]], confirmed and augmented his father's gift on the death of his wife, Clemence of Mayenne, and his departure for the [[Holy Land]] in 1190.

The foundation was confirmed by Popes [[Pope Alexander III|Alexander III]] in 1165, [[Pope Urban IV|Urban IV]] in 1264, [[Pope Clement IV|Clement IV]] and [[Pope Boniface VIII|Boniface VIII]]. Among the privileges of the monks was that of electing the [[abbot]] and the [[prior]], which they took care to have confirmed in 1498 by [[Louis XII of France|Louis XII]].

The abbey was soon the richest of the Cistercian houses of Anjou and Maine, thanks to the generosity of the lords of Sablé, Château-Gontier, Laval, Craon, Sillé, Anthenaise and Rohan. 

The abbey was suppressed and sold off as a national asset in 1793.

