'''Fri Norsk Scene''' was a [[theatre]] group consisting of Norwegian actors residing as refugees in Sweden during [[World War II]]. It was established in 1944, and was active until May 1945. The group was led by [[Halfdan Christensen]].<ref name=snl>{{cite encyclopedia |year=2007 |title=Fri norsk scene |encyclopedia=Store norske leksikon |publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget |location=Oslo  |url=http://www.snl.no/Fri_norsk_scene |language=Norwegian | accessdate=7 September 2009 }}</ref> Among the theatre's productions were [[Henrik Ibsen|Ibsen]]'s play ''[[The Master Builder]]'' ({{lang-no|Bygmester Solness}}), [[Bjørnstjerne Bjørnson|Bjørnson]]'s ''Geografi og Kjærlighet'' and [[Arnulf Øverland]]'s ''Venner''.<ref name=nbl-hc>{{cite encyclopedia|year=2003|title=Halfdan Christensen |encyclopedia=[[Norsk biografisk leksikon]]|first=Trine |last=Næss |editor=[[Knut Helle|Helle, Knut]]|publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget|location=Oslo|url=http://www.snl.no/.nbl_biografi/Halfdan_Christensen/utdypning|language=Norwegian|accessdate=7 September 2009}}</ref>

